segments.text: I mentioned that before, because I over-commit myself always.
And they were not over-committing themselves at all.
So I pushed them.
I pushed Susan to get books in earlier than was comfortable, to push the printers and push the binders.
And I pushed Noel to get more manuscripts in, not to reject them because we don't have time to review them.
And I pushed them on their dates and said, we've got to have things done earlier.
And so we just pushed and pushed and worked on increasing acquisitions.
And we took risks.
I pushed them to take risks with their selections and with the quantities.
We did that quest for the presidency.
And GALA wanted to publish 15,000, and I pushed them to publish 25,000, which they did.
And somewhere in between is what we ended up selling.
We went over 15,000, but we didn't get up to 25,000.
But I wanted them to feel the commitment and the excitement and the push.
I think that's going to go well.
It's been an old concept of the series and the idea.
I think Marilyn has basically directions
That's exciting.
That was another new thing that we got into was that whole George Bush connection.
I won't take credit for having started that connection, but I do think that I really pushed them to strengthen that connection.
Yeah, it's so obvious.
I think there's so many areas in New Orleans that have failed to really count, including this bridge.
I don't think we don't have a thing.
Oh, I don't think so.
And that quest for the presidency, that had to be done in impossible time constraints.
We had to do from start to finish in six months on that book.
And everybody said it can't be done.
It can be done, but it can be done.
But it was done.
I've seen it done.
Not here, necessarily.
I said the commercial publishers can do it, but I can't read it.
And I think if Rick Stetter had been there, they would have let it go.
They wanted to do it.
They were excited about it.
And it was one of the most fun things that we did.
That was when we got to, several of us got to go to
What's her name?
Catherine Graham's home in Washington, D.C., and we had the coming out party, and George Stephanopoulos was there, and Cokie Roberts was there, and it was wonderful.
It was really glamorous.
That story is the only excitement.
Oh, I know.
That's great.
That's good.
And it can be known.
That's good.

Okay, we worked on minimizing conservatism, and then the important thing is I tried to, in the team building, to emphasize that internal customer, and I mentioned that to you also, that our customers first are one another, because if I'm not serving your needs, you're not going to get your job done.
And so we all recognized that we were serving someone else's needs inside the press, and then finally we had an external customer.

okay so that's what i did that's what i tried to do and i think that's what we succeeded at doing that sounds really good now at some point uh we're going to search for a new director at what point and why and when did you signal that how did that happen um well i think um
The original intention was that I was going to go in and kind of bring them together as a group and clean up their finances, too, because they had serious financial problems.
I didn't even mention that, but we worked on that constantly, trying to figure out the finances and get them into reasonable financial shape.
There was an audit going on at the time.
Were they doing that?
There were two things going on.
First of all, prior to my getting there,
When I was working with Rick, we also did an operational review.

We took this group that reported to me, and I've neglected to mention that because that was a big part of it also, this operations analysis that reported to me at the time that I was meeting with Rick, and they did an operational review during which they discovered all the turmoil in the organization.
At the same time, internal audit went in and did an audit, and they discovered
that nobody knew anything about what was going on with the bookkeeping and the finances and all of that.
It wasn't being handled properly, and there were some serious issues

uh checks and balance problems and things like that so we continue to have internal audit come in and help to fix all those we brought in people from the fiscal office to help us to figure out a better accounting system that is not my strength and that's not the strength of anyone in the press it is tom's now yes
So I wasn't real successful in getting the proper accounting system in, but I was successful in getting some accountability and in getting us to open up the books.
Because no one but Diana Hine knew what existed.
So we started discussing the finances in these weekly staff meetings, and everybody got a much better understanding of what we really had and didn't have.
Because she had them convinced that they were
really in the red.
And of course we had these enormous balances
in all these accounts that we weren't doing anything with.
And some of that still exists.
I talked to her the other day.
Just an aside, I picked up that there was accounts that are really being unused.
Oh, there are.
And so what we try to do is...
I'm sure Tom will send them those in due time.
Well, and what I encourage Tom to do is to focus on getting some of that money out of there.
And some of that might be by opening up the parameters of those accounts like we did with the...
He talked about money a little bit, incidentally, and his view that the press is doing very well financially, as compared to other presses, quite secure, and that he plans to tell the world about it.

I said, I think that's good, Tom, because I think if people understand that you've been financially accountable, et cetera, et cetera, then you should get more respect and more support from the administration.
He said, well, a lot of people around here think that if you tell people how much money you have, they'll try to take it away from you.
That's true.
Or what they'll do is take away any kind of assistance that they're given.
That's right, yeah.
And so that still exists within the press.
I heard that mentioned several times, that they're going to lose their operations money because they're doing too well or something like that.
And Trump says, no, I'm not going to deal with it that way.
You're doing well, and I want the world to know I don't.
So that's interesting.
I knew all the auditing was going on in the United States.
In fact, one of the ways that we lured Tom here, and lure is the right word, and I'll get into it.

Well, I was going to say one of the ways that we lured him here is that I kept insisting to him that we were financially sound and that the university was financially supportive of the press and that we had almost a guarantee that they would not financially neglect the press.
Yeah.
And see, that was certainly one of the worries.
And I'm sure had he walked into the staff, that fear would have been communicated very strongly.
So he needed that.
Right.
That's right.
Well, he wouldn't have come without it.
He would not come.
Because we really had to thank him to come.
I mean, we just bent over backwards, and he said no twice, and we kept going back at him.
Okay, how did you find him?
What was the process?
Okay, this is sort of, everything about this is just the personal touch, and it's interesting.
I said, I was sent in to build a team and try to pull the finances together and put together a strategic plan.
And we knew that we weren't going to start a search until that was done.
So when we were about maybe almost a year into my being there, we said, now it's time to start a search.
And Bowen was here at the time.
And Jerry was my boss.
And they both said to me, would you like that job?
And I said, I would love that job.
I love the press, but I'm not what the press needs.
I said, the press needs someone who knows publishing.
I've done what I can do for it.
Now they need someone
who can take them to the next level.
Because I said, I think that they have maximized what they can do at the level where they are, and now they need to get into some new, really exciting publishing.
And I can't do that for them.
Because they said, if you would like the job, you've done such a good job, everybody there loves you, you may stay.
And I thought, well, this is the most fun job I have ever had in my life.
That's a tough decision for you.
Well, it was...
It was, it was and it wasn't.
It wasn't because I knew that they needed better than me.
Number one, even though they really did, all of them came in and begged me to stay.
But number two, I like being involved in a million different things in the university, and I didn't want to let go of that.
I knew if I'd stayed at the press, then I'd be out of everything else.
I like that.
Which is part of their glory.
Oh, that's right.
They like it that way.
They like it that way, that's right.
But I would have missed...
the thread of the university.
Because I like all this stuff.
So anyway, we advertised in a lot of different places.
And we got in lots of different applications.
But we had a search committee.

and it was chaired by Fred Heath, and we had wonderful people on this search committee, and everyone kept saying, and what we did was we got nominations, and was, I can't remember who it was, who said that Tom Rotell's name had been suggested.
And so someone had asked him to submit an application, which he did.
And I don't think he was serious about it, but he sent it in.
And we all discussed things like, well, he's the second highest or the highest paid director in the country.
Can we afford him?
He does a wonderful job there, but why would he move?
He might even be thinking about retirement because he's, you know, so he may not be interested in taking on a new challenge like this.

So anyway, we narrowed the list, and we kept coming back to Tom Rotell, and I don't know that anybody was seriously considering him at the beginning, but whoever was his champion on the search committee kept bringing his name, and of course, there was no reason to reject him because he was wonderful, but
We didn't know that he would even be as serious.
And so when we narrowed the list, he was on it.
And he might even have been the last person that we brought in.
But if not, he was the second to last.
And we brought some down.
And they were good.
But everybody was hot and cold.
Some people really liked this one.
Others didn't like them at all.
Tom came in.
Everyone loved him.
Everyone.
Incidentally, he said he got an email from you.
Yes, he did.
And he said, I think part of his response was, if anybody is that enthusiastic about a school or a class, I need to go see.
Because he said, I really wasn't thinking.
I really needed to do that.
Well, that's what I was going to say.
We were on this network.
And I forget what it was called, but this publishing network.
Oh, that drove me crazy, also, on the job, because it seemed to me like publishers had nothing more to do than to sit and write these very long treatises over the Internet.
Because these things would be just, you know, take you 20 minutes to read them, and you'd get 20, 30 of them a day.
Oh, that's one good thing about writing this history.
Wardlaw and Lyman loved to write letters.
That's all they did.
Well, that's all these publishers did.
That's what they did.
They didn't have email.
Well, because of that, I had Tom Rotell's address.
And so I did write him a very long email.
And actually, I didn't write it to him.
I wrote it to everybody out there.
I put it on the internet.
Oh, OK. And I said, I really encourage all of you.
This is a wonderful press.
We have very talented people.
The university is very supportive of it.
Because at the time, they were all talking, they were all agonizing over internet.
It was funny to read.
They were agonizing over their dwindling resources and the fact that the universities were pulling away their support, and they were in these dumpy little environments.
They didn't know what they were going to do.
And with electronic publishing, oh, moaning and groaning.
And I was writing and saying, I encourage you to apply here.
We are in a beautiful building.
The university gives us financial support.
They've committed to it.
It's wonderfully talented people.
We've got nowhere to go but up.
It's exciting.
And so that's what, yes, and that is what made Tom Rotel.
And then Tom and I communicated a couple of times.
Well, then we offered him the job after a very lengthy interviewing process.
We offered him the job, and he turned it down.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Oh, yes, he turned it down.
So we went back at it again, and I got on the phone with him, and we tried to a couple of times, and Bill Perry got on the phone with him.
We brought him back again.
We offered him the job again.
And I believe he turned it down again.
Or if he didn't turn it down, he just, yes, he was very cool.
Until we finally put together a package.
We gave him a salary that was way more than we thought the press could afford, and certainly way more than they'd have paid me if I had taken the job.
If I had known I could make that much money, I'd have had to say yes.
We gave way more than we ever dreamed of paying.
Journalism kicked in some money.
Bill Perry, the library kicked in some money.
So we put together a wonderful package for him and we said he better be good.
And he took the job and everyone in the press was unanimous.
He was their first choice.
There was not a single person who had put someone else ahead of him.
That's good.
That's a good one.
So that's how we ended up where we did.
And when I left, I left
without looking back, because I said it was a wonderful experience, but they've got the right person there now to do what needs to be done.
I think so.
I think he still remains to prove himself in a way, but it's going to be really interesting.
He fancies himself, and probably is.
They manage him.
And he says, I'm really more of a, you can call him a micromanager, since he's trying to tell everybody what to do.
He's hands-on.
To refine and...

And I think that's exactly what they needed, because I didn't know how to tell Susan how to do better the publishing part of it, and I didn't know how to work with Mary Lynn and doing the editing, and I certainly didn't know how to work with authors and doing the acquisitions, and so he has the talent
To develop those people.
He has the knowledge and the skill to develop the talent, further develop their talents.
I didn't have that.
All I could do was to give them the motivation to work on developing their own talent.
But I couldn't give them the technical.
Well, there's such a strong base in the street area.
The vigil is enormous.
It really is.
It is.
And it's still exciting.
That's what I say.
I just hope that they're still having as much fun as they were having when I was there.
Well, that's hard to do.
And you know, someone...
Scholarly and a commercial press.
And so, because before I got there, I really didn't even understand what the purpose of this press was.
Well, I was going to ask you about that.

Did you have a, from the administrative perspective, what was their view, and I think that view had changed indeed with the then current administration from what it had been with Vandiver and with Jack Williams, you know, the regular patrons in the press.
And the new administration really was not.
And Bowen, I think, is probably the press would never be one of his favorite things.
No.
No, that's right.
So that world has changed, and the press, for example, does now report to the provost instead of to the president.
And that was my idea, as a matter of fact, because when you report to the president,
Especially if it's a president that's not one of your supporters, you get nothing.
You get no attention, you get nothing.
Whereas reporting to the provost kind of ensured that ongoing financial support, and it ensured that scholarly approach.
They were very, very apprehensive about that change.
And I kept saying to them, relax, you'll like it better.
But they felt like they were being demoted.
Yes.
And it was my suggestion.

It was part of our operational review that suggested that they be taken from the president and given to the provost, where they could get some visibility and some attention and not just, you know, Rick would go to the president's staff meetings and his claim to fame was that he poured the coffee there.
And I'm very serious.
Everybody said, Rick Stetter does the coffee.
And he would tell you himself, my only role in that staff meeting is to pour the coffee.
But now, I'm hoping
that Tom has built a strong relationship with Fred Heath at the library, and with Bill Perry, and with the dean.
I mean, that's where he belonged.
Yeah, I think you're probably right.

I think one of the problems, as I said, and I think this came up in the conversation with several people, in fact, is still that the scholarly community, the Texas A&M academics, don't still have much sense of what the press is,
and what it does for them or to them or anything else.
It's amazing, but it's still isolated.
I read something just yesterday on the Aggie Hotline.
I was going to ship it over to Mary Lynn and say, what's going on here?
And then I didn't.
But it was where one of our history professors has recently, is just now publishing a book that he got some kind of a,
fancy grant to do on Tejanos and something else down at the border, and it's being published by University of New Mexico Press, and I was going to say, what's going on here?
We've got our Borderlands series that would have fit in perfectly.
No, it wasn't Bob.
Oh, I know who it is.
It's Armando Alonso.
Yes, that's exactly right.
I think that's what it was.
I don't know why he went there.
Well, New Mexico's a wonderful place.
Yeah, sure.
But, you know.
Why in the world wasn't Tom over in the history department talking about that?
Or someone.
Mary Lynn, she's the borderlands person.
Good point.
Yeah, they really need to work on that.
And I don't quite know what the solution is.
One of the perceptions that indeed, maybe most press editors have, directors have, is that the
The faculty are never supportive.

I've seen that in the writing of your operations, which is one of the reasons Wardlaw is so terribly interested in trying to fix his association to other levels, to the former students, for one thing, and to the administration.
But the administration and former students are not interested.
Some of them are interested in scholarly press, but most of them would rather see
the glitzy commercial kinds of publications.
Sure, that's right.
I know I asked John Lindezzer, why in the world are you so supportive of the French?
I said, do you like books?
He said, no, I don't like books.
He said, I like A&M.
And what does he support?
He supports the artsy kinds of things.
Yeah, oh, sure.
He doesn't support the scholarly stuff.
No, no.
And so does Joe Moore.
Right, right.
And that's okay.
I'm not knocking that.
I mean, I like that, too.
And, you know, I'm not interested in reading those scholarly books.
But when I got there, I recognized, because before that, if you had talked to me about the press, I'd have said, oh, that old boring stuff.
No wonder they don't make any money.
They don't print anything that's interesting.
When I got there, I realized I'd learned the value of the scholarly press.
And now my impression is that
is that this needs to be a scholarly press.
And it can be a premier scholarly press.
And I'm disappointed if Tom is not doing his job in this community with promoting the scholarly aspect.
Because that's what I thought he could do that I can't.
I think he is aware of that.
And I think he is working in that direction.
And I think it's particularly concerning in relation with the scholarly community and building that relationship.
He's very proud, for example.
But he also is concerned about selling books, which you have to do.
Well, and that's a balance that the whole press realizes.
That's kind of a fun balance.
It is, yeah.
It makes it a real challenge.
That's right.
You have to maintain credibility and also accountability in a very literal financial sense.
That was always a fun thing for us to discuss, too, as a press was, OK, this doesn't really fit into the scholarly mission, but on the other hand,
It's borderline.
Look at how much money we can make on this.
And everybody acknowledged that they loved to do
